<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-798-918  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 798 918.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Oct 23 1989 v23 n43 p43(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Computer crime fight stymied; conference goers decry lack ofcooperation between law and security pros. (the 12th NationalComputer Security Conference)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Alexander, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Speakers at the 12th National Computer Security Conference held inBaltimore in early Oct 1989 claimed more cooperation is neededbetween information system security practitioners and lawenforcement officials to stem the increase in computer-relatedcrime.andP;  National Center for Computer Crime Data (NCCCD) Dir JayBloomBecker told conference attendees that only six percent ofserious computer security incidents are actually reported.andP;  Thecost of computer crime in the US is estimated by the NCCCD at $555million annually, plus 930 years of personnel time and 15.3 yearsof computer time lost.andP;  Law enforcement officials attending theconference, sponsored by the US National Institute of Standardsand Technology and the National Computer Security Center, claimthe dearth of computer crime prosecutions is the result ofreluctance on the part of victims to report the crimes.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer CrimeConferencesTrendsUnited States. National Institute of Standards and TechnologyUnited States. National Computer Security CenterNational Center for Computer Crime Data.andO;Person:    BloomBecker, Jay (addresses, essays, lectures).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>